Data Structure: Explained 
A data structure is a particular way of organising and storing data in a computer so that it can be 
accessed and modified efficiently. More precisely, a data structure is a collection of data values, 
the relationship among them, and the functions or operations that can be applied on the data.  
1 
2 
Asymptotic Analysis 
There are many aspects which you must consider when designing and developing software 
applications. These include user friendliness, modularity, security, maintainability, etc. However, 
one of the most important aspects is performance, because without performance you cannot 
achieve the other aspects (stated above). 
Knowing the complexity of an algorithm allows you to answer questions such as: 
How long will a program run on an input? 
How much space will it take? 
If the problem is solvable? 
 
How do we compare two different algorithms that perform the 
same task? 
One method is to run the algorithms on your computer with different inputs and see which 
finishes in a shorter time. However, using this method you cannot check the performance of the 
algorithms for every possible input.  
Asymptotic Analysis (AA) 
AA is the method that is used for analysing algorithms. In AA we evaluate the performance of an 
algorithm in terms of the input size (we dont measure the actual running time). We calculate, 
how the time (or space) taken by an algorithm increases with the input size. 
AA shortcomings 
AA is not perfect, but it's the best way for analysing algorithms. For example, let's say there are 
two sorting algorithms that take 1000logn and 2nlogn time respectively on a machine. Both are 
asymptotically same (order of growth nlogn). So, with AA, we cant judge which one is better as 
we ignore constants in AA. 
 
AA: explained using a sorting example 
I will describe the analysis below using a linear search algorithm:  
2 
3 
 
1.Worst case analysis - in the worst case time, we calculate the upper bound on the 
running time of an algorithm. We must know the case that causes maximum number of 
operations to be executed. For linear search, the worst happens when the element you 
are searching for is not in the list. Therefore the worst case running time would be (n). 
2.Average case analysis - in average case analysis, we take all the possible inputs and 
calculate computing time for all of the inputs. Then get the average of those times.  
3.Best case case analysis - in the best case analysis, we calculate the lower bound 
running time of an algorithm. We must know the case that causes the minimum number 
of operations to be executed. In linear search the best case occurs when we are looking 
for the first element in the list. So the time complexity in this case would be (n). 
 
The average case is not easy to do in most of the practical cases and it is rarely done. In 
the average case we must know (or predict) the mathematical distribution of all possible 
inputs.  
The best case analysis is bogus. Guaranteeing a lower bound on an algorithm does not 
provide any information as in the worst case, an algorithm may take years to complete.  
 
The main idea behind AA is to have to measure efficiency of algorithm to be implemented and 
time taken by programs to be compared.  
 
Notations  
The three following notations are mostly used to represent time complexity of algorithms: 
1. notation- the theta notation bound a function from the above and below. E.g. 3n^3 
+6n^2 +6000 = (n^3) 
2.Big O notation - defines an upper bound for an algorithm, it bounds a function only from 
the above.  
3. notation - just as Big O provides an asymptotic upper bound, provides an 
asymptotic lower bound.  
3 
4 
 
Common orders of growth  
Some common orders of growth seen often in complexity analysis are: 
 
Space Complexity 
The space complexity is the amount of space used by the algorithm. 
Array 
An array is a collection of items stored at contiguous memory locations. The idea is to store 
multiple items of the same type together. This makes it easier to calculate the position of each 
element by simply adding an offset to a base value, i.e., the memory location of the first element 
of the array (generally denoted by the name of the array).  
 
Advantages and Disadvantages 
Advantages 
1.It is used to represent multiple data items of the same type by using only a single name 
(the array name). 
4 
5 
2.It can be used to implement other data structures (ADTs) such as linked list, stacks, 
queues, trees, graphs, etc. 
3.You can use multi-dimensional array, to represent objects such as matrices.  
Disadvantages 
1.We must know in advance how many elements are to be stored in array.  
2.Array is a static structure. It means that array is of fixed size. The memory which is 
allocated to array can not be increased or reduced.  
3.Since array is of fixed size, if we allocate more memory than requirement then the 
memory will be wasted.On the other hand, if we allocate less memory this will create 
problems.  
4.The elements of arrays are stored in consecutive memory locations. Insertion and 
deletions are very difficult and time consuming.

Search Time  
O(n) for sequential search, O(n log n) for binary search (if the array is sorted).  
Insertion Time 
O(n), the worst case occurs if an element is inserted at the beginning of the array and we have 
to move all the elements.  
5 
6 
Deletion Time 
O(n), the worst case occurs when we have to delete the first element and we have to move all 
other elements one index.  
 
Linkedlist 
A linkedlist is a linear data structure (like arrays) where each element is a seperate object. Each 
element (called a node) contains at least two items, the data and a reference to the next node. 
A linked list has two notable nodes called the head and the tail, the head is the first node in the 
list and the tail is the last node in the list.  
Types of Linked Lists:  
Singly linked-list: in a singly linked-list each node contains an element and a pointer to 
the next node. The node that has a pointer of null is called tail node. 
 
Doubly linked-list: in this type of linked-list each node stores an element, a pointer to 
the next node and a node to the previous node.
 
Circular linked-list: - circular linked list is a variation of linked list in which the first 
element points to the last element and the last element points to the first element. Both 
singly and doubly linked list can be converted into circular linked list. 
 
6 
7 
Space and Time complexity 
The time/space complexity is the same for both singly and doubly linked list.

Array vs Linked list 
Array contains the following limitations:  
1.The size of the array must be know in advance before using it in the program.  
2.Increasing the size of the array is a time taking process. It is almost impossible to 
expand the size of an array at run time.  
3.All the elements in the array need to be continuously stored in the memory. Inserting any 
element in the array needs shifting of all its predecessors.  
Linked list is the data structure which can overcome all the limitations of an array. Using linked 
list is useful because,  
1.Allocates memory dynamically. All the nodes of linked list are non contiguously stored in 
the memory and linked together with the help of pointers.  
2.Sizing is no longer a problem since we do not need to define its size at the time of 
declaration. List grows as per the programs demands and limited to the available.  
Linked list is ideal for when there is frequent operations such as add, delete and update. One 
drawback of linked list is that data access is sequential.  
 
 
Abstract Data Type (ADT) 
An abstract Data Type is a mathematical model of a data structure that specifies the type of 
data stored, the operations supported on them, and the types of parameters of the operations. 
An ADT defines what each operation does, not how it does it. The opposite of ADT is a 
Concrete Data Type (CDT), which is an implementation of an ADT.  
Examples: Array, List, Map, Queue, Set, Stack, Queue, Tree, Vector,etc. These ADTs have 
many implementations, i.e. CDTs.  
Real-life example: Book is abstract (Telephone book is an implementation).  
 
 
7 
8 
Stack 
Is a collection of objects that are inserted and removed according to the last-in-first-out (LIFO) 
principle. There is a distinct element called top. 
Operations 
Push(e): insert the element e at the top of the stack. 
Pop(): removes the element at the top of the stack.  
size(): number of elements in the stack.  
isEmpty(): returns true if the stack is empty and false otherwise. 
Top(): returns the element at the top of the stack, it does not remove it.  
You can implement a stack using an array or a singly linked-list. 
 
Applications 
Browser back button 
Reversing a word 
Undoing something 
Complexity 
 
Access  
Search 
Insertion 
Deletion

O(n)

Queue 
Is a collection of objects that are inserted and removed according to the First-In-First-Out 
(FIFO) principle. There are two distinct elements called front and rear.  
Operations 
Enqueue(e): inserts an element e at the rear of the queue. 
Dequeue: removes the element from the front of the queue.  
8 
9 
size(): number of elements in the queue. 
isEmpty() 
front() 
You can implement queue using an array or linked-list.

Variations: Double-ended queue 
Is an ADT that generalises a queue, for which element can be added to/removed either from the 
back and the front.

Tree 
One of the disadvantages of using an array or linked list to store data is the time necessary to 
search for an item. Since both the array and Linked list are linear data structures, the time 
required to search a linear list is proportional to the size of the data set (n), we could also 
include the n number of comparisons. 
9 
10 
Imagine doing a search on an array of size n = 10^6 nodes. Even on a machine that can do 
million comparisons per second, searching for m items will take roughly m seconds. This is not 
acceptable in todays world where speed at which we complete operations is extremely 
important. Time is money. Therefore it seems that better (and more efficient) data structures are 
needed to store and search data.  
Definition 
A tree is an ADT that stores elements hierarchically. With the exception of the top element, each 
element in a tree has a parent element and zero or more children elements. The top element is 
usually called the root.  
 
Ordered Tree 
A tree is ordered if there is a linear ordering defined for the children of each node, that is, we 
can identify the children of a node as being first, second, third, etc.  
 
Tree Traversal 
Traversal is the process of visiting all the nodes in a tree. There are three different ways we can 
perform this operation: 
In-Order Traversal 
 
Pre-Order Traversal 
 
10 
13 
Why use BST over Array or Linked-List 
BST is much faster than an array at search, insert and delete (O(log n) vs O(n)). 
BST is slightly slower than an array at access (O(log n) vs O(1)). 
BST can search, access and delete data elements in logarithmic time (O(log n)). 
 
Priority Queue 
A priority queue is an ADT for storing a collection of prioritised elements that supports arbitrary 
element insertion bu supports removal of elements in the order of priority, that is, the element 
with the first priority can be removed at any time.  
A priority queue is a collection of (key, value) entries. The fundamental methods of a priority 
queue are the following:  
insert(k,x) 
removeMin() 
isEmpty() 
min() 
Applications of priority queue include dijkstra's algorithm.  
Heap 
The heap is a special case of binary tree data structure where the root node key is compared 
with its children and arranged accordingly, is a has child b then key(a)>= key(b). As the value of 
the parent is greater than that of the child it generates the max heap. 
Min-heap

Collison 
If two or more key hash values correspond to the same index, a collision occurs.  
There are two different ways to handle a collison: 
Separate chaining - each bucket in a bucket array points to a list (this could be an array 
or linked-list). 
Open addressing - when a new key collides, find next empty slot and put it there.

Dictionary 
Like a map, a dictionary stores key-value pairs, which we call entries. Map only allows unique 
keys whereas dictionary allows non-unique keys.

Graph 
A graph is made up of two elements called nodes and edges 
There are different types of graphs: 
Undirected graph 
Directed graph 
Cyclic graph: a graph with at least one cycle. 
Weighted graph 
Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) - a graph without cycle.
